body:
@KenjiTakahashi #3292 retrieves row count for each segments targeted by a select query, something like

```
"result" : {
   "segmentCounts" : {
     "array_2016-04-09T09:00:00.000+09:00_2016-04-10T09:00:00.000+09:00_2016-05-10T02:31:21.509Z" : 3,
     "array_2016-01-18T00:00:00.000+09:00_2016-01-19T00:00:00.000+09:00_2016-07-05T10:50:43.457+09:00" : 1,
     "array_2016-01-04T00:00:00.000+09:00_2016-01-05T00:00:00.000+09:00_2016-07-05T10:50:43.381+09:00" : 1,
     "array_2016-03-09T09:00:00.000+09:00_2016-03-10T09:00:00.000+09:00_2016-03-24T06:08:49.668Z" : 3,
     "array_2016-01-11T00:00:00.000+09:00_2016-01-12T00:00:00.000+09:00_2016-07-05T10:50:43.436+09:00" : 1
   },
   "totalCount" : 9
```

So if we should acquire 3 rows, we can set just the first segment id, not using whole interval. Currently it's not accepting paging spec but we can support that with some more works, I believe. This process even can be automated in druid broker, that we are testing on select query with union datasource.

@navis I see. Would that work per partition (i.e. within segment) as well? Theoretically, it could, as select code does not seem to differentiate between segments and partitions at all.

@gianm Oh, OK. If we don't care about ordering then it would indeed work. Maybe in specific cases it would be possible to store data in a way that comes out as "pre-sorted", given that we know in what order partitions will be read. Or, if the data is partitioned on dimension, maybe use the method @navis proposed to "cut" `threshold/num_of_partitions` items from each partition and merge client-side.

I'm afraid that reading time from everything would still take significant amount of time. It would be some improvement, but we're looking for as much as possible here :-).
